PRESIDENT Jacob Zuma wants answers from the Office of the Public Protector over how an audio recording featuring him being interviewed by former public protector Thuli Madonsela on state capture landed in the hands of a television station.The interview was conducted a few days before Madonsela s aborted move to release the report.Zuma had gone to court to block the release of the state of capture report, saying he wanted to interview some of the witnesses who gave evidence against him, and to get more evidence.Yesterday, Zuma said he has lodged a complaint with the Office of the Public Protector after he discovered that the audio recording of the meeting he had with Madonsela was leaked to eNCA.Zuma s spokesperson, Bongani Ngqulunga, said the Presidency wanted to know how the recording ended in the hands of the television channel. The Presidency has sought clarity from the Office of the Public Protector on the policy of the institution regarding the release of audio recordings of interviews conducted during the course of investigation, said Ngqulunga. Present at the meeting were Zuma and his legal team, including advocate Bonisiwe Makhene and Mike Hulley.Madonsela was accompanied by her investigators at the meeting.